<main>
  <!-- Definition -->
  <details data-color="blue" open>
    <summary>
      <div class="summary-title">
        <h2>‚ú® Definition</h2>
        <span>What is a determiner?</span>
      </div>
    </summary>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p>A <strong>determiner</strong> is a word placed <strong>before a noun</strong> to show <strong>how much</strong>, <strong>how many</strong>, <strong>whose</strong>, <strong>which</strong>, or <strong>what kind</strong> of noun we mean. Determiners <em>specify, identify, or quantify</em> nouns.</p>
      <p><strong>Example:</strong> <em>This</em> book, <em>three</em> pens, <em>the</em> moon.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Types -->
  <details data-color="teal">
    <summary>
      <div class="summary-title">
        <h2>üîπ Types of Determiners</h2>
        <span>Major categories with examples</span>
      </div>
    </summary>
    <div class="section-body">
      <h3>1. Articles</h3>
      <p><strong>a</strong>, <strong>an</strong>, <strong>the</strong></p>
      <ul class="bullets">
        <li><strong>a</strong> ‚Äî before consonant sounds (a boy, a car)</li>
        <li><strong>an</strong> ‚Äî before vowel sounds (an apple, an hour)</li>
        <li><strong>the</strong> ‚Äî specific or unique items (the sun, the Taj Mahal)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>2. Demonstratives</h3>
      <p><strong>this, that, these, those</strong> ‚Äî point to specific nouns.</p>

      <h3>3. Possessives</h3>
      <p><strong>my, your, his, her, its, our, their, whose</strong> ‚Äî show ownership.</p>

      <h3>4. Quantifiers</h3>
      <p><strong>some, any, much, many, few, little, several, all, both, enough</strong> ‚Äî indicate quantity or amount.</p>

      <h3>5. Numbers (Cardinals & Ordinals)</h3>
      <p>Cardinals: <strong>one, two, three‚Ä¶</strong> ‚Ä¢ Ordinals: <strong>first, second, third‚Ä¶</strong></p>

      <h3>6. Distributives</h3>
      <p><strong>each, every, either, neither</strong> ‚Äî used to talk about individuals in a group.</p>

      <h3>7. Interrogatives</h3>
      <p><strong>which, what, whose</strong> ‚Äî used to ask questions.</p>

      <h3>8. Definite Quantifiers</h3>
      <p><strong>all, both, half, double</strong></p>

      <h3>9. Relative Determiners</h3>
      <p><strong>whose, which</strong> ‚Äî used in relative clauses.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Important Points -->
  <details data-color="gold">
    <summary>
      <div class="summary-title">
        <h2>üî∏ Important Points</h2>
        <span>Key rules and exam-friendly tips</span>
      </div>
    </summary>
    <div class="section-body">
      <ul class="bullets">
        <li>A determiner always comes <strong>before a noun</strong> (or before adjectives that modify that noun): <em>the beautiful garden</em>.</li>
        <li>Determiners are <strong>different from adjectives</strong> ‚Äî adjectives describe quality; determiners limit or identify.</li>
        <li>Every <strong>singular countable noun</strong> must have a determiner: <em>I saw a boy.</em> (not *I saw boy*).</li>
        <li>Both <code>a/an</code> are chosen by sound, not by the letter: <em>an hour</em> (vowel sound), <em>a university</em> (consonant sound 'y').</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Examples -->
  <details data-color="red">
    <summary>
      <div class="summary-title">
        <h2>üìö Examples in Sentences</h2>
        <span>Short and clear examples for practice</span>
      </div>
    </summary>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p><strong>This</strong> house is mine. (demonstrative)</p>
      <p>She bought <strong>two</strong> dresses. (number)</p>
      <p><strong>My</strong> father is a teacher. (possessive)</p>
      <p>There isn‚Äôt <strong>much</strong> water left. (quantifier)</p>
      <p><strong>Every</strong> student must submit homework. (distributive)</p>
      <p><strong>Whose</strong> bag is this? (interrogative)</p>
      <p>He is <strong>the</strong> best player in the team. (article)</p>

      <div class="example">
        <strong>Example note:</strong> To identify a determiner, ask <em>Which? Whose? How many? How much?</em> If the word answers one of those, it is a determiner.
      </div>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Quick tip -->
  <details data-color="blue">
    <summary>
      <div class="summary-title">
        <h2>üìù Quick Tip for Exams</h2>
        <span>One-line revision</span>
      </div>
    </summary>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p>If a sentence has a singular countable noun, ensure there's a determiner (a/an/the/my/this/every/etc.). Use the question words <em>Which? Whose? How many? How much?</em> to spot determiners quickly.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

